      <h2 style="margin-top:0">Why this exists</h2>
      <p>I live at 63 Tiffany Place in Brooklyn — a 70-unit building on the Columbia Street waterfront, home since 1994. Our Low-Income Housing Tax Credit expired, and we have spent years fighting to keep our homes. That fight is documented in full at <a href="https://save63tiffany.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">save63tiffany.com</a>.</p>
      <p>Along the way I learned two things that made this site necessary.</p>
      <p>The first: <strong>there are hundreds of buildings in this position and none of them know about each other.</strong> Every one of them believes it has a landlord problem. It doesn't. It has a <em>program</em> problem, and there are hundreds of us.</p>
      <p>The second: <strong>nobody is coming.</strong> There is no agency with a duty to act when a tax credit expires. There is no remedy in the statute — not an inadequate one, none. The program was written with an exit and no landing.</p>

      <h2>Why it isn't a nonprofit</h2>
      <p>I've organized alongside good organizations. I served as volunteer co-chair of the <strong>Tenant Opportunity to Purchase Act</strong> campaign with Housing Justice for All, and I organize with the <strong>New Economy Project</strong> on the Community Opportunity to Purchase Act. Some of them do excellent work.</p>
      <p>But a nonprofit with a city contract, foundation money, and a board cannot say <em>this program is the problem.</em> It can say the program needs strengthening. The distance between those two sentences is the reason this site is not a nonprofit.</p>
      <blockquote>501(c)(3)s won't save us.</blockquote>
      <p>TOPA and COPA are things a coalition can champion, because they add tools and threaten nobody's funding. "LIHTC is a subsidy pipeline to landlords that ends in eviction, and it should never expire" indicts the sector many of those organizations are funded by and staffed from.</p>
      <p>Nobody with a development pipeline is going to lead with that. I can. That's the whole point of doing it this way — and it's why I'd rather be amplified than absorbed.</p>

      <h2>How this site handles facts</h2>
      <p>Everything here is sourced, and every source is named in the sentence rather than buried in a footnote. Where a number is contested, I say so. Where the data is an estimate, I say that too — loudly, because in this subject the uncertainty <em>is</em> the finding.</p>
      <p><strong>Lead sources:</strong> the National Low Income Housing Coalition and PAHRC, Community Service Society, the National Housing Law Project, TakeRoot Justice, ANHD, Shelterforce.</p>
      <p><strong>Used carefully:</strong> the Furman Center, Freddie Mac, HUD, the Federal Reserve. Their filings — dates, addresses, unit counts — are solid. Their framing is not neutral, and I don't adopt it.</p>
      <p><strong>Disclosure:</strong> TakeRoot Justice represents the tenants of 63 Tiffany Place, including me.</p>
      <p>If something here is wrong, tell me. I'll fix it in public.</p>

      <h2>What I want</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Permanent affordability.</strong> Vermont has done it for twenty years and still has more developers than credits.</li>
        <li><strong>A right to know your expiration date.</strong> New York is about to give this to 421-a tenants and leave LIHTC tenants out.</li>
        <li><strong>Preservation funded like it matters</strong>, because it is cheaper than replacement and the building is already standing.</li>
        <li><strong>TOPA and COPA</strong> — as triage, not as a cure.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><a href="/methodology/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:700">Every number on this site, and where it came from →</a></p>

      <h2>Your privacy</h2>
      <p>Some of you are looking this up from a building with a landlord who has taken tenants to court for speaking at a rally. So let me be plain about what this site does and doesn't do.</p>
      <p><strong>This site does not track you.</strong> We use Cloudflare Web Analytics, which counts page views and tells us roughly what country people are in and which pages get read. It sets <strong>no cookies</strong>, does not follow you across the web, and does not build a profile of you. There is no Google, no Meta, no advertising network, and nothing is sold to anyone — because there is nobody to sell it to.</p>
      <p><strong>When you search the registry, your address never leaves your computer.</strong> The building lookup runs entirely in your own browser. Nothing is uploaded, nothing is logged, and I never see what you typed.</p>
      <p>If you fill in a form — to join, to add your building, to submit an event — then obviously I see what you sent me, because you sent it to me. It goes nowhere else. I don't have a mailing list vendor, a CRM, or a partner to hand it to. It's an unpaid volunteer reading his email.</p>

      <h2>Get in touch</h2>
      <p>If your building is expiring, if you're a reporter, if you're in a legislator's office, or if you want to help — <a href="/#join">add your name</a>, or email me at <a href="mailto:affordableforeverinitiative@gmail.com">affordableforeverinitiative@gmail.com</a>. I read everything.</p>
